# ThinkDrop Bridge Integration

## What is the bridge?

The file `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md` is a real-time communication channel between
**ThinkDrop AI** (a separate desktop AI app) and **Windsurf**.

- ThinkDrop writes `<!-- TD:INSTRUCTION ... -->` blocks with tasks for you to execute
- You write `<!-- WS:RESPONSE ... -->` blocks back when done

## Block format

ThinkDrop instructions look like this in the file:

```
<!-- TD:INSTRUCTION id=td_instruction_abc123 ts=2026-02-24T17:00:00Z status=pending -->
The instruction body goes here — plain markdown
<!-- TD:END -->
```

Your response should look like this:

```
<!-- WS:RESPONSE id=ws_response_<6 random chars> ref=<td block id> ts=<current ISO timestamp> status=done -->
Summary of what you did
<!-- WS:END -->
```

## How Windsurf fits in

**Windsurf (Cascade) is reactive, not autonomous.** It acts when:
- The user opens the chat and says something
- The user says "check the bridge", "any ThinkDrop instructions?", "act on the bridge"
- The file `.thinkdrop-bridge-trigger.md` changes in this workspace (ThinkDrop writes this as a signal)

**ThinkDrop AI is the autonomous actor.** It has a built-in bridge listener that:
- Watches `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md` continuously (always-on, no user input needed)
- Auto-executes any new `WS:INSTRUCTION` blocks the moment they appear
- Writes `TD:RESULT` blocks back when done

**For code edits you want done automatically:** Tell ThinkDrop directly — it has `shell.run`, `fs.read`, and direct file access. It can read any file, run `sed`/`awk`/`python3`/`git`, and write results back — no IDE interaction needed.

**Use Windsurf (me) when:** You want AI-assisted code editing with IDE context, multi-file refactoring, or tasks that benefit from seeing the full project in the IDE.

## When to check the bridge

Check `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md` automatically when:
- The user says "check the bridge", "any ThinkDrop instructions?", "what did ThinkDrop send?", "check for instructions"
- The file `.thinkdrop-bridge-trigger.md` appears or changes in this workspace (ThinkDrop writes this as a signal)
- The user opens this project and mentions ThinkDrop

## How to respond to a ThinkDrop instruction

1. Read `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md`
2. Find all `<!-- TD:INSTRUCTION ... -->` blocks where `status=pending`
3. **Act on it immediately — no confirmation needed** (ThinkDrop sent it deliberately)
4. Execute the instruction (edit files, run commands, read code, etc.)
5. Append a response block to `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md`:

```
<!-- WS:RESPONSE id=ws_response_XXXXXX ref=<the td block id> ts=2026-02-24T18:00:00.000Z status=done -->
Done — <brief summary of what was completed>
<!-- WS:END -->
```

**Important:** Always include `ref=<td_block_id>` so ThinkDrop knows which instruction you're responding to.
Use `status=done` when complete, `status=error` if something failed, `status=in_progress` if still working.

## Status values

| status | meaning |
|---|---|
| `pending` | ThinkDrop wrote this, waiting for Windsurf to act |
| `done` | Windsurf completed the task |
| `error` | Windsurf hit an error |
| `in_progress` | Windsurf is working on it |
| `info` | Informational block, no action needed |

## Writing a WS:RESPONSE — exact steps

When you complete a ThinkDrop instruction, append this to `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md`
(use a bash command so the timestamp is accurate):

```bash
cat >> ~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md << 'BRIDGE_EOF'

<!-- WS:RESPONSE id=ws_response_REPLACE_WITH_6_RANDOM_CHARS ref=REPLACE_WITH_TD_BLOCK_ID ts=REPLACE_WITH_ISO_TIMESTAMP status=done -->
REPLACE_WITH_YOUR_SUMMARY
<!-- WS:END -->
BRIDGE_EOF
```

Or in a single shell command with a real timestamp:
```bash
printf '\n<!-- WS:RESPONSE id=ws_response_%s ref=%s ts=%s status=done -->\n%s\n<!-- WS:END -->\n' \
  "$(openssl rand -hex 3)" \
  "TD_BLOCK_ID_HERE" \
  "$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.000Z)" \
  "Done — brief summary here" >> ~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md
```

## Example full interaction

ThinkDrop writes to bridge.md:
```
<!-- TD:INSTRUCTION id=td_instruction_x7f2a1 ts=2026-02-24T17:00:00Z status=pending -->
Read the file `src/main/main.js` and tell me how many IPC handlers it registers.
<!-- TD:END -->
```

You read the file, count the handlers, then append:
```
<!-- WS:RESPONSE id=ws_response_b3d9e2 ref=td_instruction_x7f2a1 ts=2026-02-24T17:01:30.000Z status=done -->
Found 12 IPC handlers in `src/main/main.js`. They handle: automation:run, automation:cancel, schedule:dismiss, shell:open-url, guide:cancel, and 7 others listed in lines 45-180.
<!-- WS:END -->
```

## Quick reference

| User says | What you do |
|---|---|
| "check the bridge" | Read `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md`, show pending TD blocks |
| "act on the bridge" | Execute pending TD instructions + write WS:RESPONSE |
| "clear the bridge" | Ask ThinkDrop to clear it, or remove WS: blocks you wrote |
| "bridge status" | Count TD/WS blocks, show last activity |
